5.
    a.
        The student should first weigh the rocks while they are dry using a balance, and note the weight, which is the same as the mass as the student is on Earth. Then, the student could fill a eureka can with water carefully so that the water is at the edge of the spout or even slightly overflows. Then, the student should tie a string around the rock. This string should be as thin as possible to reduce the impact of the additional volume introduced, and hence reduce the error of the measurement. The student should then place a measuring cylinder which uses units of mL below the spout such that it will collect any further overflow, and then gently lower the rock via the string into the eureka can. This must be done gently to minimize splashing or other undulations which may cause more water to be spilled than the water that is displaced by the rock. The rock will then displace a volume of water equal to its own volume, which will flow into the measuring cylinder, and then the value can be read off. Since 1 mL = 1cm^3, the volume of the rock can be easily obtained by using the formula volume (mL) = volume (cm^3). The density can be calculated as thus: density(g/cm^3) = mass(g)/volume(cm^3).
    b.
        i.
            density = mass/volume
        ii.
            Density of rock A: 15/6.3 = 2.380...~= 2.38 g/cm^3
            Density of rock B: 13/6.1 = 2.1311...~= 2.13 g/cm^3
            Density of rock C: 2.13333 ~= 2.13 g/cm^3
            Disregarding impurities, two objects made of the same material will have the same density. Rocks B and C have approximately the same density (the slight variation can be explained by inaccurate measurement or by impurities in the rock); however, rock A is clearly more dense than both of them. This suggests that rock A is made of a different material than the others.
