        ii.
            Because beta radiation is more likely to be blocked by the flesh and skin of the patient, as it is less penetrating.
    c.
        It is likely to be safer as it has a lower half-life and only emits gamma radiation. Gamma radiation is not ionizing, whereas beta radiation, which iodine emits, is ionizing; ionizing radiation has the potential to damage cells and cause cancer, so therefore iodine is less safe as it emits iodine radiation. Iodine has a half-life of 8 days whereas technecium has a half life of only six hours; this means that for any given amount of radioactivity required at the time of administering the testing, the patient will be exposed to less radioactivity and for a lesser time, as shorter half life means faster decay. This also means the radioactive substance will disappear from their body sooner. So, the patient is exposed to a lower dose of radiation with technecium, so it is safer.
