        ii?
            The rubber-band returns to the same extension when it is fully unloaded, so it must be the case that no plastic deformation occurred, so the rubber band must be elastic.
    c.
        i.
            13^2 = 0^2 - 2(-10)s.
            s = 8.45 ~= 8.5 meters
        ii? [What is the reactive force?]
            As the rubber band reaches its maximum height, its weight exerts a downwards force. This causes the band to accelerate downwards. As the band moves through the air as it falls, air particles rub against or collide with the band, causing drag, an upwards force which resists the downwards force and acceleration due to its weight. Since the band does not reach terminal velocity, however, this drag-force is always lower than the force of its weight. Since the forces on the rubber band are not balanced, the rubber band increases in speed downwards as it falls. As the rubber band hits the ground, the ground exerts a reaction force against the rubber band, stopping it from going through the ground.
10.
    a.
        The wires in the coil move and cut perpendicularly through the field lines of the magnet, which induces a voltage in the coil. Since each half of the coil is moving in an opposite direction, voltage and therefore flow of current are induced in opposite directions physically (but which is the same direction along the wire). This causesa the ammeter to read a small current.
    b.
        i.
            There is a diode in the circuit as alternating current produces a current which continually changes direction, and to charge a battery direct current is needed, which always flows in one direction. The diode allows flow of current only in one direction and disallows flow in the reverse direction, and hence creates a current which does not continually change direction; i.e. a DC current.
        ii.
            The coil will cut through the field lines of the magnets at a greater speed, so a higher voltage and current will be induced, so the current in the battery will increase.
    c.
        14000/8400/7.2 = 0.2314... ~= 0.231A
11.
    a?
        The motion of gas molecules is random, so at any given moment roughly the same amount of gas particles proportional to the area of the wall are colliding with each wall at roughly the same average and total speed. Since mass is (roughly) equal, and momentum is roughly equal, we know the forces exerted on each wall is roughly equal, proportionally, and so therefore pressure is constant.
    b.
        current volume = 130/8.4*5 = 77.3809...; pressure is inversely proportional to volume; ratio of initial to current volume = 130/(130/8.4*5) = 1.68; so ratio of current pressure to initial pressure must be 1.68, so current pressure must be 1.68 * 100 = 168 kPa.
12.
    a.
        1800/16% = 11250 is the total energy;
        11250 * (1-16%) = 9450J wasted.
    b.
        Insulating material such as styrofoam could be wrapped around the beaker to prevent loss of heat via conduction to the beaker and from the beaker to whatever is holding the beaker, and the inside of that material could be painted silver to prevent loss of heat via radiation; A lid with a suitable hole for the boiling tube (made again with styrofoam to fit with an airtight seal, or as close to as possible): this prevents loss of heat via convection. Preventing loss of heat to the environment makes it more efficient as now the only place for the heat to go is into the boiling tube.
    